            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVI.R16</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>&ldquo;Compagnon de la Majolaine&rdquo;</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-dc48af92-7fff-f38c-a5c1-499ca2101cbc\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This chapter returns us to the use of the song in the novel&rsquo;s very opening chapter, included in the Notes (see LD.I.R7), thus helping this chapter to &ldquo;throw the interest back to the first chapter&rdquo; as he indicates below. Dickens uses the song as a strategy to spark Cavalletto&rsquo;s recognition; Arthur finds himself &ldquo;unconscious of having repeated it audibly&rdquo; after hearing Rigaud singing it in Book II, chapter 10 (No. XIII); Cavalletto picks up the song, leading to the recognition of Blandois&rsquo;s identity.&nbsp;</p>"
